                  <h5> <a name="gov"></a>Government </h5>
                  <p>The country is administered by the New Zealand Ministry of 
										Foreign Affairs. The ministry appoints an Administrator for 
										a three year term. But the country's most important institution 
										is the General Fono (assembly) made up of representatives 
										of the three atolls of Tokelau: Atafu, Nukunonu and Fakaofo. 
									<p>Each island sends 6 delegates to the General Fono  including the Faipule (chairman of the Council of Elders, or Taupulega) and the Pulenuku (Village Mayor). All the delegates are elected by popular vote for a three-year term. The General Fono meets at least twice a year and approves the general budget. 

<p>The 3 Faipule form the Council of Faipule and represent Tokelau at the international level. The position of Ulu o Tokelau (Head of Tokelau) is rotated annually among the 3 Faipule.  

<p>With New Zealand encouragement, Tokelau is moving progressively towards self-government and economic self-sufficiency. Tokelau is on the list of the United Nations Decolonising Committee.



                  <h5><a name="res"></a>Resources<br>
                  </h5>
                  <p>Due to its small size, its isolation and lack of natural resources, Tokelau relies on New Zealand to fund its public services and its development program. New Zealand accounted for 80% of Tokelau's budgetary resources in 1999-2000. 

<p>The population lives in a traditional subsistence economy. The only exports are small quantities of copra, handicrafts, coins and stamps. The sale of fishing licences to vessels operating within Tokelau's Exclusive Economic Zone has become, in recent years, an increasing source of income. Another important source of revenue comes from remittances from family members living overseas (essentially in New Zealand where 5,000 Tokelauans are established).




                  </p>
                  <h5><a name="hist"></a>History </h5>
                  <p>According to local oral traditions, the 3 atolls forming today's Tokelau were settled from three different 'homelands': Samoa, Rarotonga (Cook Islands) and Nanumanga (Tuvalu). 

<p>Commodore John Byron was the first European to come across the islands in 1765. 

                  <p>During the 19th century, the atolls were visited by a succession 
                    of whalers, explorers, beachcombers and missionaries. Nukunonu 
                    was converted by Catholic missionaries from Wallis Island, 
                    Atafu by Protestant missionaries from Samoa, while on Fakaofo 
                    both religions co-exist. 
                  <p>Like other islands in the region, the three atolls were raided in the 1860s by Peruvian 'blackbirders' searching for slave labour. They were formally placed under British administration in 1889 before becoming part of the newly formed Gilbert and Ellice colony in 1916. 

<p>The islands were officially designated as Tokelau islands in 1946. In 1948, they were included in the territory of New Zealand. 







                  <h5>Main Issues </h5>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <p>small size of population, coupled with emigration to 
                        New Zealand <br>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
